

<section xml:id="sec_conic_sections">
  <title>Conic Sections</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      The ancient Greeks recognized that interesting shapes can be formed by intersecting a plane with a
      <em>double napped</em> cone (i.e., two identical cones placed tip<ndash />to<ndash />tip as shown in the following figures).
      As these shapes are formed as sections of conics,
      they have earned the official name <q>conic sections.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The three <q>most interesting</q>
      conic sections are given in the top row of <xref ref="fig_nondeg_conic">Figure</xref>.
      They are the parabola, the ellipse
      (which includes circles)
      and the hyperbola.
      In each of these cases, the plane does not intersect the tips of the cones
      (usually taken to be the origin).
    </p>
<!--
<caption>Conic Sections</caption>
